<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What blood type is the universal donor?", answer: "O-negative (O-) is the universal red blood cell donor because it lacks A, B, and Rh antigens, meaning it will not trigger an immune reaction in any recipient. O- blood can be safely transfused to patients of any blood type, making it critical for emergency situations when there is no time to determine the patient's blood type." },
  { question: "What blood type is the universal recipient?", answer: "AB-positive (AB+) is the universal recipient for red blood cell transfusions. Because AB+ blood already has A, B, and Rh antigens, the immune system will not attack donor blood of any type. AB+ individuals can receive red blood cells from all eight blood types." },
  { question: "How is blood type determined?", answer: "Blood type is determined by the presence or absence of A and B antigens on the surface of red blood cells, and the Rh factor (D antigen). Type A has A antigens, Type B has B antigens, Type AB has both, and Type O has neither. The Rh factor adds the positive (+) or negative (-) designation. Blood type is inherited from parents and does not change over a lifetime." },
  { question: "Can blood types affect pregnancy?", answer: "Rh incompatibility can affect pregnancy when an Rh-negative mother carries an Rh-positive baby. The mother's immune system may produce antibodies against the baby's Rh-positive blood cells, potentially causing hemolytic disease of the newborn in subsequent pregnancies. This is prevented with RhIG (RhoGAM) injections during pregnancy and after delivery." },
  { question: "What is the rarest blood type?", answer: "AB-negative (AB-) is the rarest of the eight common blood types, found in only about 0.6% of the population. The most common blood type is O-positive (O+) at 37.4%, followed by A-positive (A+) at 35.7%. Blood type distribution varies significantly by ethnicity and geographic region." }
]) %>

